      <h3>Dangerous Wild Life</h3>
      <h1>Wolves</h1>
      <img src="/wolvesFrance.jpg" alt="Wild Boar" class="smaller-image">
      <p>Wolves are found in the southeast and eastern regions of France, especially in the Alps and the Pyrenees. They are shy and fearful of humans, and attacks are very rare. </p>
    <a href="#" class="read-more">Read Full Post</a>
    <div class="full-content">
      <p>However, they can be aggressive if they feel threatened or if they are protecting their territory or pups. To avoid encountering wolves, stay on marked trails, keep your distance from any signs of wolf activity, and do not feed or approach them. If you see a wolf, do not run or turn your back, but stand tall, make noise, and slowly back away.</p>
    </div>
    <h1>Asp vipers</h1>
        <img src="/aspViperFrance.jpg" alt="Ticks" class="smaller-image">
      <p> Asp vipers are venomous snakes that live in rocky areas and dry grasslands in southern France. They are brown or grey with dark zigzag patterns on their backs and can grow up to 80 cm long.</p>
    <a href="#" class="read-more">Read Full Post</a>
    <div class="full-content">
      <p>They are active during the day and hunt by ambushing their prey. Their venom can cause severe pain, swelling, bleeding, and tissue damage. To avoid asp vipers, wear long pants and boots when hiking, watch where you step or sit, and do not touch or disturb any snakes. If you are bitten by an asp viper, seek medical attention immediately.</p>
    </div>
