  <h3>Natural Disasters</h3>
  <h1>Floods</h1>
      <img src="/floodFrance.jpg" alt="Tornedoes" class="smaller-image">
      <p>Floods can happen anywhere in France, but some of the most affected areas are the French Riviera, Bordeaux, and the Atlantic coast.</p>
    <a href="#" class="read-more">Read Full Post</a>
    <div class="full-content">
      <p>Floods can cause damage to property, infrastructure, and transportation, as well as injuries and deaths. To prevent floods, France has invested in improving its flood defences, such as dams, dikes, and levees. However, these defences are not always sufficient or well-maintained, and some areas are still vulnerable to flooding. </p>
    </div>
    <h1>Heat waves</h1>
        <img src="/heatWaveFrance.jpg" alt="storms" class="smaller-image">
      <p> Heat waves are becoming more frequent and intense in France due to climate change. Heat waves can cause dehydration, heat exhaustion, heat stroke, and death.</p>
    <a href="#" class="read-more">Read Full Post</a>
    <div class="full-content">
      <p> Heat waves can also increase the risk of wildfires or droughts. The most affected areas by heat waves are the urban areas and the south of France. To prevent heat waves, France has a heat wave plan that activates when the temperature exceeds a certain threshold for several days. The plan includes providing information and advice to the public, opening cooling centres and shelters, distributing water bottles and fans, and reducing greenhouse gas emissions. </p>
    </div>
