        <h1>Local laws and customs</h1>
      <img src="/lawFrance.jpg" alt="Queuing Etiquette" class="smaller-image">
      <p> France has some laws and customs that may be different from your home country. You should always carry a photo ID with you, such as your passport, as the police may conduct random checks.</a> </p>
    <a href="#" class="read-more">Read Full Post</a>
    <div class="full-content">
      <p> You must also stop to help if you witness an accident or someone asks for help, unless doing so will put you or others in danger. It is illegal to cover your face in public places or force someone else to do so. This includes wearing masks, helmets, burqas, niqabs, or other face-covering garments. It is also illegal to photograph security forces, such as the police or the military. You may face fines or imprisonment if you break these laws.</p>
    </div>
    <h1>Terrorism and security</h1>
        <img src="/terrorisimFrance.jpg" alt="Mind the Gap" class="smaller-image">
      <p> France has a medium level of threat from terrorism, and attacks could happen anywhere and at any time. </p>
    <a href="#" class="read-more">Read Full Post</a>
    <div class="full-content">
      <p> You should be vigilant and alert in public places, especially those that are crowded or frequented by tourists, such as monuments, museums, markets, transport hubs, and religious sites. You should also avoid demonstrations and protests, as they may turn violent and result in clashes with the police. If you hear or see anything suspicious, report it to the authorities immediately.</p>
