        <h3>Etiquette</h3>
        <h1>Dining</h1>
      <img src="/diningFrance.jpg" alt="Football enthusiasm" class="smaller-image">
      <p>Dining is an important part of French culture, and there are some etiquette rules that you should follow when eating out or being invited to someone home. </p>
    <a href="#" class="read-more">Read Full Post</a>
    <div class="full-content">
      <p>You should always wait for the host to say “Bon appétit” (enjoy your meal) before starting to eat, and not use this phrase yourself as it may be considered rude1. You should keep your hands visible on the table, but not your elbows. You should use the cutlery from the outside in, and place them parallel on your plate when you are finished. You should not cut your bread, but break it with your fingers. You should not eat too fast or too slow, and finish everything on your plate. You should not ask for a doggy bag, as it is not common in France. You should also compliment the food and the host, and offer to help with the dishes.</p>
    </div>
    <h1>Gifts</h1>
        <img src="/giftFrance.jpg" alt="Photography of People" class="smaller-image">
      <p>If you are invited to someone’s home for a meal or a party, it is customary to bring a small gift for the host, such as a bottle of wine, a box of chocolates, or a bouquet of flowers. </p>
    <a href="#" class="read-more">Read Full Post</a>
    <div class="full-content">
      <p> However, you should be careful with your choice of flowers, as some may have negative meanings in French culture. For example, you should avoid giving chrysanthemums, as they are associated with death and funerals. You should also avoid giving red roses, as they imply romantic interest. You should also avoid giving an even number of flowers, as it is considered bad luck. Instead, you should give an odd number of flowers, except 13.</p>
